AB  - Aim: To explore the changes of blood gas indexes of basketball players of Chinese University Basketball Association (CUBA) in various hypoxia conditions. Methods: Ten healthy male basketball players, who participated in the training of the basketball team of Hunan Normal University, aged (20.3±1.3) years, body height (190.6±5.9) cm, body mass (80.57±7.77) kg, training time (6.0±1.8) years, without experience of living in high altitude for generations, were selected. After maximal exercise, the subjects were given graded 2 hours of hypoxia for one week. The blood gas indexes at quiet state were measured on the next day after training with 30 minutes, interval between 2 players and one person each time: 1The players pulled ligament for 5 minutes after 13 minutes of warm-up, which referred to 8 minutes running around the basketball ground with heart rate of 120 times per minutes. 2Maximal exercise for 20 minutes: Return exercise of foot movement with freehand for the whole ground. 3The blood gas was immediately tested after maximal exercise, which was finished in one minute with mean heart rate of 189 times per minute. 4After the test, the players entered the hypobaric oxygen chamber for 2 hours, followed by collection of brachial artery blood to test the blood gas indexes in hypoxia condition (PO2 14.6 and 11.2 kPa). The blood gas analyzer was used to measure the base excess (BE), base excess of extracellular fluid (BEecf), buffer base (BB), HCO3- and pH value. Results: Ten players all entered the result analysis. 1Comparison of blood gas indexes at quiet state and the immediate moment after maximal exercise: The indexes, which represented the buffer capacity, including BE, BEecf, BB, HCO3- and pH value were decreased after maximal exercise, but there was no significant difference (P&gt; 0.05). 2Comparison of blood gas indexes at the immediate moment after maximal exercise and hypoxia condition (PO2 14.6 kPa): The BE, BEecf, BB, HCO3- and pH value were increased after intervention of hypoxia at immediate moment after maximal exercise, but there was no significant difference (P &gt; 0.05). 3Comparison of blood gas indexes at the immediate moment after maximal exercise and hypoxia condition (PO2 11.2 kPa): The indexes, which represented the buffer capacity, including BE, BEecf, BB, HCO3- and pH value were decreased after maximal exercise, but there was no significant difference (P &gt; 0.05). 4Comparison of blood gas indexes between PO2 14.6 and 11.2 kPa condition: With the increase of hypoxia, the indexes, which represented the buffer capacity, including BE, BEecf, BB, HCO3- and pH value were obviously increased, but there was no significant difference (P &gt; 0.05). Conclusion: 1The buffer systemic capacity increases after 2 hours hypoxia following maximal exercise in normal oxygen condition. 2With the increase of hypoxia (PO2 14.6 kPa decreased to 11.2 kPa), the buffer capacity significantly increased. 3The involvement of hypoxia after maximal exercise in normal oxygen condition is an effective method to make the buffer system appear well adaptive changes, which can provide some evidence for the training of basketball players in CUBA.
