AB  - Animals representing a complete diallel cross among 4 inbred strains of Mus musculus were measured for 9 traits which potentially contribute to thermoregulation. Correlation matrices were estimated on males and females separately for general combining abilities, specific combining abilities, maternal effects, and residual error. There were a few differences between correlations in males and females which reflected differing amounts of additive or dominance effects on the individual traits, and the fact that females had more significant general combining ability, body weights were negatively correlated with physiological traits and positively correlated with each other. Nesting was correlated with body temperature and oxygen consumption, and negatively associated with weight gain and food consumption. Correlations of additive genetic effects are important factors in evolutionary adaptation, even in pairs of traits which have been important to fitness. Correlations of dominance deviations may further elucidate the extent of genetic coupling of fitness-related traits.-from Authors
