AB  - 1. A comprehensive reheat furnace model has been developed to determine the slab temperature evolution, the thermal stress, the dissolution temperatures, the heating speed, the furnace temperature profiles and the optimal residence time. These features provide a powerful tool for optimization of reheat furnace heating practices. 2. Two new heating criteria were created to address the lower temperatures of the skidmarks to avoid rolling load fluctuation and to ensure complete dissolution of the microalloy particles. 3. The effects of the curved skid riders were taken into account in the model, and the results indicate that the curved skid riders can help to alleviate the skidmarks by about 20°F and reduce the residence time by about 2 minutes. 4. The thermal stresses the slab experiences under typical Mobile furnace conditions would not be likely to cause cracking unless there are already preexisting defects in the slab. 5. It was interesting to reveal that, for slab reheating, depending on the temperature level and temperature homogeneity, a higher discharge temperature may require less residence time than that needed for a lower discharge temperature. This is opposite to what was commonly believed, that a lower discharge temperature would reduce residence time. 6. Thorough heating practice modifications were made by regrouping the heating families, decreasing or increasing the target discharge temperatures, reducing the minimum residence time and creating new heating practices. 7. The implementation of the modified practices to IPSCO's Mobile reheat furnace has exhibited an overall residence time savings of 12.3 minutes. This translates to a productivity increase of 8.8% and a substantial financial benefit.
