AB  - Data of Ballhaus, Berry, and Green's oxygen barometry and Mössbauer spectroscopy were used to identify the redox state of dunites and chromites of the Nizhnii Tagil (dunite body of Mount Solov'eva) and Kytlym (Iov, Kos'va, and Sosnovka bodies) massifs in the Ural Platiniferous Belt and of the Uktus Massif, which does not belong to the belt. The accuracy of a series of olivine-chromite geothermometers (Roedder et al., 1979; Fabries, 1979; Ballhaus, Berry, and Green, 1991) was tested empirically, and correcting coefficients for them were proposed, which make it possible to take into account the effect of Ti on the partition of Fe and Mg between the phases and, thus, to make the calculated temperatures consistent with one another and with geothermometric data. The thermal evolution of the dunites during the development of the Platiniferous Belt was revealed, including the origin of autonomous dunite bodies over the temperature range 900-1100°C, their subsequent integration into dunite-clinopyroxenite-gabbro blocks (products of accretion at 700-800°C), and the development of platiniferous mineralization at 700-800°C. The analysis of these data reveals broad variations in the redox state of the inspected dunite and chromite samples, with the oxygen fugacity one to four orders of magnitude above the FMQ buffer. The redox parameters of ultramafics show variations within the belt as a whole, individual massifs, and blocks (for the Kytlym Massif). For example, at iron mole fractions of the Cr-spinel and olivine of 60 and 8%, respectively, the oxygen fugacity (logfO2 relative to the FMQ buffer) of dunites from various massifs is as follows: 2.6 for the Mount Solov'eva body, 2.2 for the Iov body, 3.0 for the Kos'va body, 2.5 for the Sosnovka body, and 1.9 for the Uktus Massif [at the Fe/(Fe + Mg) ratio of 60 and 8% for Cr-spinel and olivine, respectively]. The oxygen fugacity values in the chromitites, which are syngenetic with the dunites and bear background PGE concentrations, are practically identical to these values of the host dunites, while the epigenetic PGE-bearing chromitites are characterized by logfO2 values higher by 1.5-2 orders of magnitude. This testifies to the existence of a geologic interlude between the origin of different chromite types and the very strongly oxidized chemistry of the fluids responsible for the PGE mineralization. The redox state of ultramafic rocks of the Ural Platiniferous Belt and the genetically related rocks of the Uktus Massif is much more oxidized than that of sublithospheric Alpine-type ultramafics, both continental and oceanic, but is identical to the redox state of island-arc peridotites. Along with materials on the mineralogy and geochemistry of the mafic rocks and the composition of the PGE mineralization, these data led us to conclude that the whole rock complex of the belt and of the Uktus Massif was produced in environments close to those of island arcs. Copyright © 2002 by MAIK "Nauka/Interperiodica" (Russia).
