AB  - A diverse population of Daphnia magna Straus was formed in the laboratory by combining individuals from eight sources (48-hour EC50s from cadmium toxicity tests with these eight groups ranged from 26 to >120 μg/L). Selection for increased resistance to the acute toxic effects of cadmium was accomplished by determining the cadmium EC50 value, exposing neonates to that concentration for 48 hours, raising the survivors in cultures without cadmium, and using their offspring to repeat the procedure. After eight generations, this selection process increased the mean EC50 from 61 μg/L to 180 μg/L cadmium. No differences in life span, offspring production, time to first brood, number of offspring in the first brood, or the intrinsic rate of population increase (r) were observed between the cadmium-adapted population and the control under ideal conditions or conditions of temperature or feeding ration stress, but cadmium-adapted daphnids were smaller. The absence of differences between the two populations other than size suggests a lack of metabolic cost for the increased resistance. Gel electrophoresis indicated the presence of metallothionein, a metal binding protein, in daphnids. Because metallothionein is an inducible protein, the lack of apparent metabolic cost might be explained if elevated concentrations of metallothionein are only produced during cadmium exposure, when increased metabolic costs would be offset by greater survival probability. The EC50 values for the control and cadmium-adapted populations were not different during acute toxicity tests with copper or malathion, but the cadmium-adapted population was less sensitive to lead and more sensitive to phenol. Amplified fragment-length polymorphism (AFLP) analysis of DNA showed a decrease in genetic diversity in the cadmium-adapted population based on the number of polymorphic markers and the calculated gene diversity, and this loss of diversity was reflected in reduced slopes of the concentration-response curves during cadmium toxicity tests. Although the evolved resistance would allow the adapted population to exist in areas where cadmium concentrations would be toxic to control daphnids, the decreased genetic diversity, smaller size, and increased sensitivity to at least one other toxicant would likely reduce the probability of long-term survival, even in the absence of future cadmium exposure.
