AB  - Researchers have proposed several theories to explain the mechanisms of injury and repair in gram-negative bacteria. Approaches have been basically twofold, involving either an examination of chemical and morphological changes in cells incurred as a result of the stress treatment, or investigation of the nutrient and physical requirements for repair. Table I11 summarizes selected research findings evolving from experiments implicating the involvement of the cytoplasmic membrane in gram-negative cell injury and repair. Leakage of intracellular constituents during exposure to stress has been noted for several species and implies a malfunction of the cytoplasmic membrane. Increased sensitivity of injured cells to uncouplers of oxidative phosphorylation and to surface-active compounds also implicates the membrane as a site of damage. To what extent these debilitations affect the survival of bacteria is not thoroughly understood. It seems likely, however, that when and if death of injured gram-negative bacteria occurs, the damaged membrane has a contributing influence. © 1978 Academic Press Inc.
